text:
Not sure about why a certain font from Google wouldn't show in the list. But to handle the selected font, you'd want something like this in your theme's base.html file:

```    &lt;link rel="preconnect" href="<https://fonts.googleapis.com>"&gt;
    &lt;link rel="preconnect" href="<https://fonts.gstatic.com>" crossorigin&gt;
    &lt;link href="<https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family={{> theme.global_fonts.primary.font }}:ital,wght@0,100;0,300;0,400;0,500;0,600;0,700;0,800;0,900;1,100;1,300;1,400;1,500;1,600;1,700;1,800;1,900&amp;display=swap" rel="stylesheet"&gt;
    &lt;link href="<https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family={{> theme.global_fonts.secondary.font }}:ital,wght@0,100;0,300;0,400;0,500;0,600;0,700;0,800;0,900;1,100;1,300;1,400;1,500;1,600;1,700;1,800;1,900&amp;display=swap" rel="stylesheet"&gt;```

*EDIT: Please disregard, I misread the question. Sorry! Please see my follow-up response for actual relevant information.*

To set max width, you’ll need to add two parameters to your `{% dnd_section %}` tag. `full_width` _(boolean)_ and `max_width` _(integer)._

To set padding and margin, you’ll need to add the `padding` and `margin` properties, respectively. Each of them accepts a dictionary containing the `default` and `mobile` properties, which in turn contain properties for each absolute direction — those absolute directions take their values as strings, including units.

Putting it all together, you should expect something like this:
```{% dnd_section
    width=12,
    offset=0,
    full_width=false,
    max_width=768,
    margin={
        "default": {
            "top": "32px"
        },
        "mobile": {
            "top": "3rem"
        },
    },
    padding={
        "default": {
            "left": "16px",
            "right": "16px"
        }
    }
%}

    ...

{% end_dnd_section %}```
